    "summary": "The Sogdian Trade Cities (c. 300–100 BC) of Central Asia (modern Uzbekistan and Tajikistan) were the commercial centers — including Samarkand, Bukhara, and Maracanda — from which the Sogdian merchant people would eventually dominate the overland [[event:1129|Silk Road]] trade, serving as the crucial intermediaries between the Chinese, Persian, Indian, and Mediterranean worlds.\n\nSogdia, the region between the Amu Darya and Syr Darya rivers, was a prosperous agricultural and commercial zone that had been part of the Achaemenid Empire and then absorbed by [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]]'s conquests (Samarkand/Maracanda was the city where Alexander killed his general Cleitus in a drunken quarrel). Under the subsequent [[event:1041|Seleucid Empire]] and then its successor states, Sogdian merchants developed the commercial networks and multilingual skills that would make them the premier traders of Central Asia for a millennium. Sogdian merchants are documented in Chinese sources from the 3rd century AD onward, but their commercial activities almost certainly began earlier; their merchant letters found at a watchtower in China (dated c. 313 AD) provide a window into a sophisticated trading diaspora connecting China to Persia.",
